WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.281 --> 00:00:08.114
(pulsating music)

00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:24.720
- If you ask, how does a brain work

00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:27.200
from an engineering perspective,

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:31.750
then you might ask, what is
the circuit diagram look like?

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:36.160
After all, if complex modern
processors are designed

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.330
and understood by engineers,
then maybe a simple brain

00:00:40.330 --> 00:00:42.540
could be likewise
understood at that level.

00:00:45.110 --> 00:00:49.240
Let's consider exactly
that, a simple processor.

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:51.270
And if you take the lid off,

00:00:51.270 --> 00:00:55.340
you'll find underneath the die, the chip.

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:56.700
Looking at it a little bit closer,

00:00:56.700 --> 00:01:00.820
you'll see that it's broken
up into various modules

00:01:00.820 --> 00:01:05.580
for processing, for input
from various sources

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:10.020
and for outputs, memory and
likewise in the control.

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:13.580
If you look at a small
region and zoom in on it,

00:01:13.580 --> 00:01:18.580
you'll find it's covered by a
vast mesh of tiny, tiny wires.

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:22.830
This is about, maybe,
a dozen layers thick.

00:01:22.830 --> 00:01:25.520
Underneath it all, there
are the actual switches,

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:29.480
the transistors, which
do the switching on this.

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:32.690
Now if you wanna make it, you just need

00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:36.300
a few billion dollars, machines like this,

00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:39.390
and you're good.

00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:41.200
If you wanna reverse engineer it,

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:43.730
then maybe you could use
some machines like this

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:46.160
as one example which I'll be discussing

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.210
in more detail called a FIB-SEM.

00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:52.990
Now on the other end, here's
another processing unit.

00:01:52.990 --> 00:01:56.750
Let's take the cover off and
underneath there's a brain

00:01:56.750 --> 00:02:00.210
and it too has various
modules in it, you know,

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:03.510
optical inputs, called optic lobes,

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:07.020
antenna inputs for smell, memory units,

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:08.410
they all have different names,

00:02:08.410 --> 00:02:11.440
mushroom bodies, ellipsoid
bodies, and so forth.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:13.380
Studied by biologists.

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:17.180
So you can also zoom in
and look very carefully

00:02:17.180 --> 00:02:18.580
and presumably, there's also gonna be

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:22.450
a vast mesh of wiring in there

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:25.140
and somehow buried in
underneath all of that

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:28.060
should be synapses, which
are switching between

00:02:28.060 --> 00:02:29.750
all of these different wires.

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:32.090
Now if you wanna make one of these,

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:34.123
you need to invest in an old banana.

00:02:34.123 --> 00:02:35.060
(audience laughing)

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:40.060
- And wait, not much cost,
and it'll self assemble.

00:02:40.090 --> 00:02:43.230
And it's amazing, and
you've heard about this,

00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:46.780
you know, in the first talk,
and it's truly amazing.

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:48.860
So now if you wanna reverse engineer it,

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:52.040
we really need, it's a tough problem,

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:54.260
and we need tools from
across the spectrum.

00:02:54.260 --> 00:02:56.420
From biology, from genetics,

00:02:56.420 --> 00:02:58.990
and I'll talk a little bit of
the aspect that can come in

00:02:58.990 --> 00:03:02.740
from the semi-conductor
industry, that FIB-SEM.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.840
So just to put a perspective,

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.130
let's put some dimensions on these

00:03:07.130 --> 00:03:09.240
and compare them side-by-side.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:13.110
A current processor is sort
of a flattened structure,

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:15.700
2 1/2 dimensions, but the volume

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:17.930
of it is under a millimeter.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:22.310
The fruit fly, it's a nice little blob,

00:03:22.310 --> 00:03:24.660
under a millimeter in size.

00:03:24.660 --> 00:03:26.930
Not too different in the volume.

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:30.840
The number of transistors
and switches in the processor

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:32.180
are getting pretty impressive,

00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:35.110
about a billion transistors nowadays.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:37.000
That's a bit more than the fruit fly.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:38.880
If you go back 10 years, the Pentiums,

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:40.820
they had about a comparable number.

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:45.050
And the last part, now, is the wire size

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:48.900
and the transistor size and the
dendrite size, synapse size,

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:52.900
they're all in the tens of nanometers.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:56.360
Very small, and the challenge
is to bridge the gap

00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:01.230
between the small size
of tens of nanometers

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:03.760
all the way up to a good
fraction of a millimeter

00:04:03.760 --> 00:04:06.290
and catch that large, dynamic range.

00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:09.320
So to reliably resolve these transistors

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.750
in all three dimensions,
we need to sample,

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:15.350
probably instead of 15 nanometers,

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:18.130
maybe at five or 10 nanometer increments.

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:21.470
These are the voxels that
you'd use to form images

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:24.490
and you've seen before,
one can sort of collect

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:27.950
many such images in 3D, form a stack.

00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:30.930
But if you just quickly
look at the numbers,

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.990
how many voxels, how
many pixels are there?

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:36.517
Eight nanometers compared
to half a millimeter.

00:04:36.517 --> 00:04:39.760
There're lots, it's a good
fraction of a pieta byte

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:41.220
and if you're acquiring the data

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:44.145
at a modest rate of a megahertz,

00:04:44.145 --> 00:04:47.010
then you'd be acquiring
data for eight years,

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:50.070
even for something simple
as a fruit fly plane.

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:51.530
Now I should also point out,

00:04:51.530 --> 00:04:54.540
we do need to really see the connectivity,

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:56.960
one needs to go down to the EM level,

00:04:56.960 --> 00:04:58.879
to the electron microscope level.

00:04:58.879 --> 00:05:02.960
Light microscopy cannot
quite resolve the details

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:05.050
and see the fine connectivity.

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:09.200
Light microscopy can do many
other things, image life,

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:11.020
so all these techniques are very

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:14.430
complementary and support each other.

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:17.090
So what is the FIB-SEM?

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:20.660
This is basically an
instrument where you use FIB,

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:22.710
which is a focused ion beam,

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:25.620
and it basically abrades away the surface

00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:27.690
a few dentimeters at a time.

00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:29.570
The advantage of an ion beam is

00:05:29.570 --> 00:05:32.000
the abrasion is just a little bit finer,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.670
more controlled, in the Z-dimension.

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:37.050
Otherwise it's very similar to what Mark

00:05:37.050 --> 00:05:40.570
was talking about earlier,
the serial block face cutting.

00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:43.080
After you abrade or remove a little layer,

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.630
you image the surface with
a scanning electron beam

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:51.500
and then you ablade again
and you cycle through this

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:55.870
about every minute, and
you keep going and going

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:58.940
for as long as you possibly
can and in the end,

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.300
you gradually reconstruct a circuit.

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:04.620
In this case, if you're looking
at a semi-conductor chip,

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:07.340
you can see all the metal layers inside.

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:10.780
If one's looking at a fly brain,

00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:14.690
then you should get a
three-dimensional reconstruction

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:16.580
of all the details inside.

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:21.160
So this here is the outline
of one of these synapses,

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.970
the black part is actually
the membrane itself.

00:06:24.970 --> 00:06:26.880
Ah, and there you can see.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:31.880
So what you saw, time
here is moving in in Z

00:06:33.740 --> 00:06:36.430
and you'll see on the
left picture right there

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:38.980
the dark spots, those are
actually the synapses,

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:43.330
they're pretty small, and this
is a typical fan in circuit,

00:06:43.330 --> 00:06:46.774
they're multiple synapses
going all onto one dendrite.

00:06:46.774 --> 00:06:49.020
And you see the opposite in the fly,

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:52.780
fan ins, fan outs, there're
just a variety of structures

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:55.690
that are all visible.

00:06:55.690 --> 00:06:59.670
It's more complex than it
is for a mammalian brain.

00:06:59.670 --> 00:07:03.680
So we got one of these
machines and started out.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:06.250
And so we ran it.

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:07.520
Three days later,

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:10.340
it came to a grinding halt and stopped.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:15.340
And so we imaged 1/1000 of a
brain and couldn't continue,

00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:19.250
there were problems, and so
we came to this conclusion.

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:21.820
- FIB-SEM's irrelevant because it can't

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:23.640
image anything useful.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:25.432
I continued to be employed.

00:07:25.432 --> 00:07:26.670
(audience laughing)

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:29.300
And worked on the next problem,

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.860
five years of reliability engineering.

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:36.130
Basically to handle all of
these interrupts as they happen,

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:38.120
can we anticipate things,

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:41.450
make graceful stops if something
bad is going to happen,

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:44.570
mitigate damage control,
and we can restart

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:46.705
without loss of anything.

00:07:46.705 --> 00:07:50.880
The bar is very high
because if you have a gap

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.939
in this dense interconnect of wiring,

00:07:53.939 --> 00:07:56.010
there's no way that you
can connect the wires

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:57.520
from the left half to the right half

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:00.020
and you're circuit
diagram is just useless.

00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:02.840
So you don't want to be
there imaging several years

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:05.840
into the project and then say oops.

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:09.240
So a few years later, here we are,

00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:13.920
imaging now for about
a three months project.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:15.500
That is looking at the optical lobe.

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:18.316
You might've noticed three pieces,

00:08:18.316 --> 00:08:20.450
madella, lobula, and lobula plate.

00:08:20.450 --> 00:08:23.840
And this is sort of what
you see inside a fly brain.

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:26.720
The motion you see is, again,

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.720
is moving in Z deeper and deeper.

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:33.890
Initially the width was about 120 microns,

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:36.380
it's about the width of two human hairs,

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.550
and in zooming in about 10x,
and we can look at detail,

00:08:40.550 --> 00:08:44.610
and for example right
there, that's a synapse,

00:08:44.610 --> 00:08:47.290
and it's connecting this dendrite

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:51.130
over to several other
guys on the other side.

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:52.520
It's all very subtle.

00:08:54.253 --> 00:08:56.130
It's a big challenge

00:08:56.130 --> 00:09:01.130
to try to pull all of that
information out and segment it.

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:04.300
So it took us three months to image this,

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:07.900
and then we gave it to some other people,

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:11.540
and about three years later,
they processed the data.

00:09:11.540 --> 00:09:14.030
Processing it and analyzing it is, by far,

00:09:14.030 --> 00:09:15.720
the bigger challenge.

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:19.160
This is not easy and it
requires a lot of hand effort,

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:22.640
or it did require a lot
of hand effort to segment,

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:26.340
curate, make sure there's
no mistake in there.

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:29.190
And what we're doing here
is dense segmentation.

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:31.650
We're getting, pretty
much, all of the processes,

00:09:31.650 --> 00:09:34.870
all of the neurons, identifying them,

00:09:34.870 --> 00:09:37.100
and then you can pull
them out, one by one,

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:38.610
and you find that they have their own

00:09:38.610 --> 00:09:42.070
unique shapes and sizes

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:46.960
and compare them to what is
known from other experiments.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:51.330
For example, some of these neurons

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.680
are coming in from the retina,

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:57.480
some of them are
sensitive to on-transition

00:09:57.480 --> 00:10:00.700
or to off-transition or
to a left-to-right motion

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:03.450
or front-to-back motion,

00:10:03.450 --> 00:10:05.900
and people can identify that

00:10:07.481 --> 00:10:09.540
based on optical imaging.

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:11.570
But optical imaging can't tell you

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:14.460
the detailed synaptic connectivity,

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:16.280
but it can give you the classes of neuron

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:20.100
so one can connect the two
and bootstrap our way forward.

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:24.470
In addition, optical imaging
can look at life samples, too,

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:26.200
and tell which ones are firing

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:28.270
on on-transitions and off-transitions

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:30.070
and we can actually monitor that.

00:10:30.070 --> 00:10:33.340
So all of that data can be put together

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:36.510
and you can begin to
identify the components

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:38.220
of a circuit diagram.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.780
And these are the three major
parts that you saw earlier,

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:43.520
the madella, the lobula,
and the lobula plate.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:45.440
Up here's the retina.

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:48.090
The thing is with the FIB-SEM,

00:10:48.090 --> 00:10:50.620
it allows you to make the
last little connection,

00:10:50.620 --> 00:10:53.060
which is to ask, here's one neuron,

00:10:53.060 --> 00:10:57.760
which we know reacts to a
left-to-right on-transition,

00:10:57.760 --> 00:10:59.340
what are its inputs?

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.220
And you can define the neurons that are

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:04.250
responsible for that,
characterize those independently,

00:11:04.250 --> 00:11:07.350
and we make this last step,
and then you can begin

00:11:07.350 --> 00:11:09.290
to test models of the circuit.

00:11:09.290 --> 00:11:14.290
Is this a coincidence detector
based on exutory inputs,

00:11:14.660 --> 00:11:17.980
is it a different version of that,

00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:19.720
a nor-detector where you might have

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.160
an inhibitory input on one side.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:24.250
And it turns out that it's a little bit

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:27.150
a combination of both are
present in the fly brain,

00:11:27.150 --> 00:11:29.480
and you can even sort of get estimates

00:11:29.480 --> 00:11:30.940
of what might be causing the delay

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:33.330
based on the length on the synapse.

00:11:33.330 --> 00:11:35.380
So having this extra level of detail

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:37.910
helps close a lot of open gaps.

00:11:37.910 --> 00:11:40.710
So so far, we still haven't
gotten to the full fly brain

00:11:41.660 --> 00:11:44.930
and we reverted to another technique

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:47.550
called hot knife sectioning
to get all the way up.

00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:50.080
Imagine the fly brain,
you chop it up into, like,

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:52.880
a loaf of bread, into about 30 pieces,

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:55.140
each about 20 nanometers thick.

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:58.390
You put it on a little laminated surface

00:11:59.370 --> 00:12:02.120
and you have about 30 of these tabs

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:04.630
and feed them in to a bunch of machines.

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:08.310
And this puts us in the range of getting

00:12:09.228 --> 00:12:11.430
this eight FIB-SEM year effort

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:14.620
maybe down to a little
bit more reasonable time.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:16.300
And we are gearing up and trying

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:19.780
to expand toward this direction here.

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:23.450
And so far, over the past two years,

00:12:23.450 --> 00:12:26.715
we've come just a little
ways along that path.

00:12:26.715 --> 00:12:29.350
Looking in here, we have what we've

00:12:29.350 --> 00:12:31.630
accomplished called a hemi brain.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:34.130
It aspires to be half a brain,

00:12:34.130 --> 00:12:35.420
but it's a little bit shy of it.

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:39.180
It's on a female fly, but it's unilateral

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:42.430
over a good part of it,
misses some aspects, you know,

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:45.480
too much on the optic lobe,
missing the parts below

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:49.090
which are associated with
feeding and appetite,

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:51.610
but a lot of modules are in there.

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:53.310
The central complex,

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:58.170
which is sort of an internal
compass for the fly,

00:12:58.170 --> 00:13:01.200
and people are studying
that independently.

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:03.580
Olfactory learning and the mushroom body,

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:07.820
lateral horns, all these
names are dear to biologists

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:10.560
studying different parts of the fly brain.

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:11.990
Here's what that looks like.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:14.430
That big round circle,
the donut that you saw,

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:15.730
that's the ellipsoid body,

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:20.390
and that's associated with its navigation,

00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:22.880
sort of an internal compass of the fly.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:25.920
And here we're just sort
of flying through the data

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:28.000
and you can just sort of see the complex.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.670
Here we're getting pretty close at this,

00:13:30.670 --> 00:13:32.210
you know, resolution isn't as beautiful

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:36.160
as what Mark has with the
dedicated high-res microscope,

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:39.970
but we're doing, right
here, as we fly in and out,

00:13:39.970 --> 00:13:41.570
that's going across that section.

00:13:41.570 --> 00:13:44.430
We have to make sure that
section has good enough quality

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:46.710
that we can match the dendrites

00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:49.217
from one side to the other without loss.

00:13:49.217 --> 00:13:50.700
That's critical.

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:55.220
And I'll just let this play a little bit.

00:13:57.071 --> 00:14:00.170
It's amazing that this thing self-wires

00:14:00.170 --> 00:14:01.700
and it looks so disorganized

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:05.230
but in the end it really is organized.

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:08.020
And there are the different
modules, we're zooming back out.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:09.590
Here you can see the whole upper head

00:14:09.590 --> 00:14:12.210
of the fly brain there.

00:14:12.210 --> 00:14:14.280
Remember, these are several slabs

00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:16.690
and we're just gonna
go through six of them,

00:14:16.690 --> 00:14:19.060
we have 13 altogether.

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:21.923
This represents about two years
of imaging that we've done.

00:14:21.923 --> 00:14:23.760
We've just sort of completed this.

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.240
And what will come next after this,

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:31.060
we want to go over, try
looking at a male fly,

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:34.901
but doing it now in its
entirety all the way

00:14:34.901 --> 00:14:37.140
and that'll be a larger imaging effort.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:41.260
And here we are back
to the central complex.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:42.850
So what's next?

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:46.190
That data is not good enough by itself,

00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:50.950
it needs some processing,
and it goes off to experts,

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:54.700
computer science experts
who use neural nets,

00:14:54.700 --> 00:14:57.180
and there've been a lot of
fascinating developments

00:14:57.180 --> 00:15:00.700
in the past few years of what they can,

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:02.600
how quickly they can extract it,

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:04.610
so they are now maybe at the level

00:15:04.610 --> 00:15:07.270
where instead of taking 10
times longer than imaging,

00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:09.430
they might almost be able to keep up

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:13.500
and pull out the nerves and get
these connectivity diagrams,

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:16.530
what nerve connects to
what, out of the thousands,

00:15:16.530 --> 00:15:19.400
hundreds of thousands to
different nerves in there

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:22.890
and give those to biologists
so that can be correlated

00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:25.370
with all the other information
that they work with.

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:30.370
So, like to put this
technology, this FIB-SEM,

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:31.980
on a little diagram like this

00:15:31.980 --> 00:15:34.600
just to show where it
might fit into the world.

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:36.790
The bottom axis is size.

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:39.930
We're looking at relative
larger size structures,

00:15:39.930 --> 00:15:43.070
it's getting close to a millimeter,

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:45.490
little bit below that for the fly brain.

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:48.030
And the vertical axis is resolution.

00:15:48.030 --> 00:15:50.420
There's some techniques out
there, as Mark talked about,

00:15:50.420 --> 00:15:52.620
which can get much better resolution,

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:56.450
but the size is going to be
a little bit more limited

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:59.930
and we're playing this trade
off between size and resolution

00:15:59.930 --> 00:16:02.450
and I think FIB-SEM has a
little bit of a sweet spot,

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:06.990
and fly brain sort of demands
some of those attributes.

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:11.789
Now the FIB-SEM can also be used

00:16:11.789 --> 00:16:15.628
in a different modality where you can

00:16:15.628 --> 00:16:18.070
operate it with lower current.

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:20.730
And in there, one might be
able to image, let's say,

00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:22.850
a whole cell with higher resolution.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:26.290
The whole cell's smaller in
volume but higher resolution.

00:16:26.290 --> 00:16:29.680
And images, instead of
being blurry like this,

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:33.970
can be somewhat crisper,
and we can see a more detail

00:16:33.970 --> 00:16:37.290
of the synapse in the
bottom slide over here,

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:41.590
like right down here, post
synaptic vesicles over here,

00:16:41.590 --> 00:16:43.970
individual ribosomes can be imaged

00:16:43.970 --> 00:16:46.590
and at the top, we can
even see microtubuals.

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:53.840
This is just a random
piece of mammalian cortex,

00:16:53.930 --> 00:16:57.040
and one can take out a part of that,

00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:59.560
segment it similar to what Mark has shown,

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:04.180
and you can get all the
intercellular organelles,

00:17:04.180 --> 00:17:07.220
endoplasmic reticula, the mitochondria,

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:12.050
and mine it for various details,

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:15.590
or the bottom, maybe even
